Text.Value: And you believe you have the right to such an understanding?

EditorData.NodeContext: Hint of an eyebrow raise - is this a sign of Gale's same old hubris?

Text.Value: You know what it is to worship her, to respect her, to love her...
Well? Are you composing a poem in your head, or some such?

EditorData.NodeContext: Impatient, but in an amused way. Gale is suddenly shy about answering his goddess / lover's call.

Text.Value: It is a corrupted, half-born magic wrought in the brief moment Karsus ascended to godhood. It hungers for power just as he did, and it can never be sated.

EditorData.NodeContext: Weighty/strong sentiment here - the Karsite Weave is an abomination in her eyes

Text.Value: I'll let Mystra show her flight, and then I can see how strong a chance we stand of winning the gambit.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Ante' and 'flight' are terms used in a d&d equivalent of poker. 'flight' = cards and 'gambitt' = round.

Text.Value: Your goddess awaits. Hear her out, but remember that you do not owe her obedience, and you certainly do not owe her your life.
So that's what you're scared of. With the Crown of Karsus reforged, I could take control of the Karsite Weave.
You abandoned me in my hour of greatest need. I had no obligation to help you in yours.
The future of magic rests on your shoulders, Gale of Waterdeep.

EditorData.NodeContext: Almost like a 'knighting' vibe - she's declaring her faith in him, and believes he can do this.

Text.Value: I promise you - it is a burden you are strong enough to bear.

EditorData.NodeContext: Almost like a 'knighting' vibe - she's declaring her faith in him, and believes he can do this.

Text.Value: You're not taking me with you?
Thankfully not. Though she's not been averse to demanding the odd human sacrifice in recent days, has she?

EditorData.NodeContext: black humour, referring to the fact she asked him to blow himself up

Text.Value: The summoning channel Mystra has provided is for me alone. No one else is permitted to enter it, no matter how talented a user of the Weave they are.
Alas, recent events have rendered the majority of it moot, so I'm going to have to improvise. Unless you have any words of wisdom to impart before I go?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Gale reaches a hand out in front of him, closes his eyes. A brilliant flash of white light and - he's in the Outer planes. Before him, Mystra in her celestial form.
EditorData.VFXTags: [DP] Weave around the statue intensifies, creating a pure stream that reaches out and passes infront of Gale as he reaches his hand out to touch it., , White flash as he is teleported to the Astral Plane., , Mystra appears behind him in a sparkle/flash of magic

Text.Value: Because you had no right to ask that of me. You cast me out, remember?
I'd pray that she'll be in a forgiving mood, if she weren't the one I'd be praying to.
You were my lover, my Chosen, yet still you know so little of me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hint of disappointment - even after all the advantages I gave you, you can't see further than your own nose

Text.Value: It's one thing for us to actually pursue the Crown. I'm not entirely sure I want to threaten Mystra with the prospect on her own turf, so to speak.
*There she stands, just as Elminster promised. Mystra. Goddess of the Weave. Mother of all magic.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player gazes up at the statue of Mystra. She appears beautiful, imposing, indifferent.

Text.Value: You unleashed something that would consume all magic in existence, and yet you thought only of preserving yourself.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Am I wrong?'. Referring back to Gale unleashing the orb, and then coming to Mystra to ask her to cure him of it.

Text.Value: With pleasure. It's not often one has the chance to threaten a goddess and make good on it.
When the Karsite Weave entered your body, your gifts were the first thing it consumed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hint of gentleness - recognising some of Gale's pain

Text.Value: You were already worthy. What you lacked was patience, and it cost you dearly.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hint of gentleness - recognising some of Gale's pain

Text.Value: You discovered what lies at the Heart of the Absolute - the Crown of Karsus - and you disobeyed my instruction. Why?

EditorData.NodeContext: Big question - this was the quest Mystra gave to the player in Act 2, which they refused to complete. Mystra containing her frustration, but needs to know the answer. 'Heart of the Absolute' was the term used for what turned out to be the brain/Crown

Text.Value: The summoning channel Mystra has provided is one only I can enter. No matter how much I'd prefer not to face her alone.
You're ready for this, Gale.
It's a summoning channel, the kind Mystra once used to call me to her side. I only have to reach for it, and it will take me to her side.

EditorData.NodeContext: Disbelief

Text.Value: The fragment of magic you tried to return to me was not of my creation. It was the Karsite Weave.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Fragment of magic' referring to the orb in Gale's chest. 'Karsite Weave' with distaste - the creation of someone she hates

Text.Value: Go on then, Gale. We'll be here waiting for you when you're finished.

EditorData.NodeContext: Encouraging, like telling a friend to go chat to their ex while you wait in the car ready to debrief after.

Text.Value: Make her squirm. Tell her the Crown will be ours soon enough.
A great ask indeed. You've given me much to think on - as you always did.
You have more faith in her than even I did... Understandable, though, when you have not loved her as deeply, or known the depths of her affections.
Your goddess calls. Serve her or denounce her as you will - but you cannot ignore her.
Go on, my good man. You can't exactly deny a goddess, now can you?
I'll only be gone for a matter of moments. The Outer Planes experience time quite differently to our own.
Mystra. I never thought we'd speak again like this. Why am I here?
The Mother of all Magic would not summon you without reason. You must hear her out.
I'd give more than a few limbs to be summoned to Mystra's presence, to look on the Mother of Magic herself...
You're right. I am a strong, capable wizard. And this is no more than a casual reunion with an ex-lover.
My concern was the preservation of everything. The Karsite Weave could tear apart the very fabric of the Material Plane.

EditorData.NodeContext: A hint of anger here - Gale's selfishness is not her own, he's pissing her off by accusing her of these motives

Text.Value: Gale of Waterdeep. You look well.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not giving much away - both a pleasantry on an awkward reunion with her ex, and carrying the added implication of the fact Mystra told Gale to blow himself up, yet he stands before her, alive and well
EditorData.VFXTags: [DP] Mystra appears as a Magical being

Text.Value: I always wondered what being nervous would feel like. I hate it.
If you will not use the orb to end this abomination, then you must find a way to separate Crown and host. When you've done this, you must surrender the Crown of Karsus to me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Key info - player quest.

Text.Value: It was intoxicating. An experience beyond expression.
The past cannot be undone with self-pity, nor can a future be forged. Only with the truth will you see the way ahead.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not letting him off easily

Text.Value: No thanks to you. I wasn't expecting a summons, but then you did always prefer things on your terms.
You don't owe her so much as a fingernail. She asked you to blow yourself up.
You're right. A heartfelt apology is the surest way to a goddess' heart, and her favour.
The old man wasn't lying. She's opened a summoning channel. Can't you feel it?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Gale looks at the statue of Mystra
EditorData.NodeContext: Can't quite believe it

Text.Value: The only reason the 'orb' sleeps is because I have allowed it to feed on the true Weave - a temporary measure, but one that will not be enough to save us.

EditorData.NodeContext: "This is what your foolishness has cost". New information for the player, who believes Mystra simply waved her hand and fixed them because it suited her.

Text.Value: Oh that hardly matters. There's not much further I could fall in Mystra's estimation. But I'd like to at least leave her with something to think about.
I won't let you down again. When the Absolute is vanquished, I will surrender Karsus' powers to you. You have my word.
Don't give anything away. Just find out what she has to say.
This won't take long, and when I'm done, I'll be free of Mystra's yoke once and for all.
You can no more control the Karsite Weave than a weather vane could control a storm.

EditorData.NodeContext: A personal warning for Gale, but not specifically that 'he' couldn't control it - no mortal could. Stern, warning

Text.Value: *Gale's right. The very air around the statue crackles with magic, as though the Weave itself were coursing beneath her stony skin.*

EditorData.VFXTags: [DP] Statue sparkle increases intensity slightly, but not Maximum yet

Text.Value: Well somebody had to. You weren't exactly forthcoming with any offers of help.
Time was I'd have given my right arm for a chance to speak with Mystra again. The left one too. Maybe a knee...

EditorData.NodeContext: Nervous

Text.Value: *There she stands. Mystra. Goddess of the Weave. Mother of all magic.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player gazes up at the statue of Mystra. She appears beautiful, imposing, indifferent.

Text.Value: So be it. Follow the needle of your own wisdom. We shall see how truly it leads you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Neutral - not impressed he hasn't outright agreed to what she asked, but willing to give him the time he needs.

Text.Value: With each day that passes, the elder brain threatens to become a new kind of god, its worshippers a scourge of soulless illithids.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hinting at the fact the elder brain will soon evolve, becoming free of the dead three's control. A terrible vision for the future.

Text.Value: Wait for me. Please.
When I pictured this moment, I thought I'd feel more in control. Yet here I am, with palms sweatier than a bugbear's armpit.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mystra's form disappears. Gale stands in an ordinary temple before an ordinary statue once more. Mystra's idol gazes on, revealing nothing. Gale smiles to himself.
EditorData.VFXTags: [DP] Mystra disappears in a big flash, forcing Gale to cover his eyes, , Statue sparkles/weave fades away as Gale smiles at his God

Text.Value: My omnipotent, omniscient ex-lover...

EditorData.NodeContext: It's getting on top of hi again, he's getting nervous again

Text.Value: You still believe yourself to be so wronged? You always were stubborn.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hint of an eyebrow raise - is this a sign of Gale's same old hubris?

Text.Value: Seek her forgiveness, Gale. It might be your only hope of curing the orb.
There is much unsaid between us, but time runs ever short.

EditorData.NodeContext: "much unsaid' carries a lot of weight - could refer to their relationship, their breakup, Gale's betrayal etc. Mystra is subtly keeping control of the conversation.

Text.Value: I don't suppose you can imagine what it's like, to have your god as your lover...
Strange... Do you feel that? It's as though the Weave itself is rushing past us...

EditorData.NodeContext: Can't quite believe it

Text.Value: Why do you care what she thinks of you?
You shouldn't go to her, Gale. Don't give her the satisfaction.
If it does not crush you, I will.

EditorData.NodeContext: Here we glimpse the true, unimaginable power of Mystra. She's still in control of herself, but her anger should be palpable.

Text.Value: I'm sure she has nothing pertinent to share whatsoever.
During my time locked away in Waterdeep, I prepared a quite comprehensive speech for her on the subject of our former relationship, and the manner in which it ended.
An audience with your goddess can go wrong - I should know - but do whatever you feel is best, Gale.
Mystra is a lesser goddess compared to Lady Shar, but if you have a chance to speak to her, you should seize it.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'An audience with your goddess ' = SH has turned from Shar. 'Mystra is a lesser goddess' = SH is loyal to Shar.

Text.Value: Am I?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The player nods firmly in response

Text.Value: Fine. If you're so against the idea, I suppose we can forge ahead without input from the goddess of magic.
Pull it together. You're going to make a fool of yourself otherwise.
Thank you. May the Weave's light guide your purpose, and its wisdom guide your hand.

EditorData.NodeContext: A blessing - Mystra relieved you'll do it

Text.Value: I did not come here to suffer a mortal's admonitions. Certainly not yours.

EditorData.NodeContext: restrained, but taking no nonsense

Text.Value: That can't be. It wasn't - it couldn't have been. I only wished to prove myself worthy. I had no idea...
Mystra won't be the one issuing the orders for much longer. She'll know exactly who's coming for her.
Even with the orb, you're one of the best wizards in the Realms. You don't need Mystra's help.
You'd make a fine Three-Dragon Ante player, you know.
Well? Go on, then - it's rude to keep a goddess waiting.
Not the message one hopes to receive from a past lover. But her first love was always the Weave. At best, I was a close second.
Confident almost to the point of arrogance I may be, but in this matter I know she'll have wisdom to share. As for whether I choose to act upon it... we shall see.
I don't think she's that kind of goddess.
*Gale's right. The very air around the statue crackles with magic. It sets your teeth on edge.*

EditorData.VFXTags: [DP] Statue sparkle increases intensity slightly, but not Maximum yet

Text.Value: That it entered your body and consumed no more than your powers was a miracle. But we will not be granted another.

EditorData.NodeContext: A hint of anger here - Gale's selfishness is not her own, he's pissing her off by accusing her of these motives. The 'miracle' is that Gale didn't do any more damage, not that he survived. Sense of foreboding on the last sentence.

Text.Value: You're kind to say so, but this is hardly my first time in Mystra's presence. It's more the matter of what I'm going to say to her.
As do you. But I assume we're not here solely to exchange compliments. So, why am I here?
This is my only opportunity to learn the truth. About the Crown, the orb, all of it. Why try to keep me from it?
Mystra's forgiveness? If you want me to claim the Crown of Karsus, she'll hardly be in a forgiving mood after that.
No doubt you yourself have sought Mystra's wisdom from time to time, but to not only receive her blessings, but her love...
For a wizard, to have the love of the goddess of magic herself...

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining/justifying himself

Text.Value: I think it's best I keep a cool head going into this. Approach it like a particularly high-risk round of Three-Dragon Ante.
Do you know what you're going to say to her?
You're right. If you want to go, you should go.
Eh... the first step is difficult, of course. Minsc could throw you in, if you prefer?

EditorData.NodeContext: Genuinely being helpful. Gale stands wondering whether to answer Mystra's summoning portal.

Text.Value: What do you mean? I've been waiting for an opportunity like this since long before our paths crossed.
I didn't want to die. And when I saw the Crown, I thought I might not have to, if I only understood its power.
Crown yourself, Gale Dekarios, and you will learn what it is to carry such weight upon your shoulders.

EditorData.NodeContext: An icy edge entering her voice - a hint at the challenge Gale will face if he pursues this course

Text.Value: Not happening. When I get my hands on that Crown, I'm going to wield it. Karsus' powers will be mine.
Of all the things to be nervous about, an audience with a goddess seems reasonable.
A stream of pure, undiluted Weave. I only have to reach out, and it will carry me to Mystra, wherever she may be.
Do what you must, Gale. Mystra has weighed upon your heart and mind for too long.
